<div id="comment_status_64175761" class="commentstatus"></div>
<div id="comment_64175761" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_64175761" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_64175761" name="comment_link_64175761" href="//science.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23199639&amp;cid=64175761" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64175761)" >Cosmological Principle</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64175761" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64175761); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>4</a>, Interesting)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~Retired+Chemist">Retired Chemist</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~Retired+Chemist">( 5039029 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64175761">		
		on Saturday January 20, 2024 @06:47PM (<span class="ind"></span><a href="//science.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23199639&amp;cid=64175761">#64175761</a>)
		<small> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64175761">The so-called Cosmological Principle (that the universe is homogeneous at sufficiently large scales) is nothing really but a simplest case assumption.  There is no real evidence for it, and now it appears that there may be evidence against.  If it is incorrect than all our models of the early universe (inflation, dark energy, etc.) have to be reconsidered since they all depend to some degree on its correctness.</div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64175761">
